================================================================================
                    UNIT TESTING - COMPLETE NOTES (ZERO TO HERO)
================================================================================

PART 1: UNIT TESTING KYA HAI? (DEFINITION)
------------------------------------------
Definition: Unit Testing ek software testing method hai jisme application ke
**smallest testable parts** (individual methods/classes) ko **isolation** mein
test kiya jata hai.

Simple Words: Ek-ek method ko alag se check karna ki woh sahi kaam kar raha hai ya nahi.

PART 2: UNIT TESTING KYUN KARTE HAIN? (BENEFITS)
------------------------------------------------
1. **Bugs Jaldi Pakadna:** Development ke time hi error mil jata hai.
2. **Refactoring Safe:** Code improve karte waqt pata chal jata hai kuch tuta toh nahi.
3. **Documentation:** Test cases batate hain ki method ka expected behavior kya hai.
4. **Confidence:** Production deploy karne se pehle sure ho jate ho ki sab sahi hai.
5. **Time Saving:** Baad mein debugging ka time bachta hai.

PART 3: TYPES OF TESTING (PYRAMID)
----------------------------------
     ┌─────────────┐
     │     E2E     │  (End-to-End) - Sabse kam, Sabse slow
     ├─────────────┤
     │ Integration │  (Services + DB) - Medium
     ├─────────────┤
     │    UNIT     │  (Single Method) - Sabse zyada, Sabse fast
     └─────────────┘

PART 4: JUNIT KYA HAI?
----------------------
Definition: JUnit Java ke liye ek **Unit Testing Framework** hai.
Ye annotations provide karta hai test methods likhne ke liye.
Spring Boot default JUnit 5 (Jupiter) use karta hai.

Dependency (Spring Boot already included):
```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-test</artifactId>
    <scope>test</scope>
</dependency>
```

PART 5: JUNIT 5 ANNOTATIONS (SABSE IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------
| Annotation | Kaam (Definition) |
|:-----------|:------------------|
| `@Test` | Ye method ek Test Case hai |
| `@BeforeEach` | **Har Test se pehle** run hoga (Object setup) |
| `@AfterEach` | **Har Test ke baad** run hoga (Cleanup) |
| `@BeforeAll` | **Saare Tests se pehle EK BAAR** run hoga (Static hona chahiye) |
| `@AfterAll` | **Saare Tests ke baad EK BAAR** run hoga (Static) |
| `@DisplayName` | Test ka custom naam (Console/Report mein dikhega) |
| `@Disabled` | Test temporarily skip karna |
| `@ParameterizedTest` | Same test multiple inputs ke saath run karna |
| `@RepeatedTest` | Test ko multiple baar run karna |

PART 6: ASSERTIONS (VERIFICATION)
---------------------------------
Definition: Assertion ek statement hai jo check karta hai ki **Expected Result**
aur **Actual Result** same hain ya nahi.

| Method | Kaam |
|:-------|:-----|
| `assertEquals(expected, actual)` | Dono values equal hain? |
| `assertNotEquals(unexpected, actual)` | Values equal nahi honi chahiye |
| `assertTrue(condition)` | Condition true hai? |
| `assertFalse(condition)` | Condition false hai? |
| `assertNull(object)` | Object null hai? |
| `assertNotNull(object)` | Object null nahi hai? |
| `assertThrows(Exception.class, () -> {...})` | Code ne expected Exception throw ki? |
| `assertAll(() -> {...}, () -> {...})` | Saare assertions ek saath check karo |

PART 7: BASIC UNIT TEST EXAMPLE (SERVICE LAYER)
-----------------------------------------------
```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.*;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

class CalculatorTest {

    private Calculator calculator;

    @BeforeEach
    void setUp() {
        calculator = new Calculator(); // Har test se pehle naya object
        System.out.println("Setup complete");
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Addition of two positive numbers")
    void testAddition() {
        // Arrange (Setup)
        int a = 5;
        int b = 3;

        // Act (Action)
        int result = calculator.add(a, b);

        // Assert (Verify)
        assertEquals(8, result, "5 + 3 should be 8");
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Division by zero should throw exception")
    void testDivisionByZero() {
        // Assert
        assertThrows(ArithmeticException.class, () -> {
            calculator.divide(10, 0);
        });
    }

    @AfterEach
    void tearDown() {
        calculator = null;
        System.out.println("Cleanup done");
    }
}
```

PART 8: AAA PATTERN (ARRANGE-ACT-ASSERT)
----------------------------------------
Har test method teen parts mein divide hona chahiye:

1. **Arrange:** Test data setup karo, objects banao.
2. **Act:** Actual method call karo jisko test karna hai.
3. **Assert:** Result verify karo.

```java
@Test
void testFindUserById() {
    // 1. Arrange
    Long userId = 1L;
    User expectedUser = new User(1L, "rahul");
    when(userRepository.findById(userId)).thenReturn(Optional.of(expectedUser));

    // 2. Act
    User actualUser = userService.findUserById(userId);

    // 3. Assert
    assertEquals(expectedUser.getUsername(), actualUser.getUsername());
}
```

PART 9: MOCKITO KYA HAI? (MOCKING FRAMEWORK)
--------------------------------------------
Definition: Mockito ek **Mocking Framework** hai jo **Fake Objects** banata hai.
Jab tumhe Database, External API, ya doosri classes ko test se **isolate** karna ho.

Important Annotations:
| Annotation | Kaam |
|:-----------|:-----|
| `@Mock` | Fake object banata hai (Dependency) |
| `@InjectMocks` | Real object banata hai + usme `@Mock` wale inject karta hai |
| `@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)` | Mockito enable karta hai (JUnit 5) |

PART 10: MOCKITO EXAMPLE (SERVICE + REPOSITORY)
-----------------------------------------------
```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.*;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.extension.ExtendWith;
import org.mockito.*;
import org.mockito.junit.jupiter.MockitoExtension;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.*;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;
import java.util.Optional;

@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)  // Mockito enable
class UserServiceTest {

    @Mock  // Fake Repository
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    @InjectMocks  // Real Service with Fake Repository injected
    private UserService userService;

    @Test
    void testGetUserByUsername_Success() {
        // 1. Arrange
        String username = "rahul";
        User mockUser = new User(1L, "rahul", "rahul@gmail.com");

        // Jab bhi repository call ho, fake response do (DB call nahi hogi)
        when(userRepository.findByUsername(username)).thenReturn(Optional.of(mockUser));

        // 2. Act
        User foundUser = userService.getUserByUsername(username);

        // 3. Assert
        assertNotNull(foundUser);
        assertEquals("rahul", foundUser.getUsername());

        // 4. Verify (Check karo ki repository method call hua ya nahi)
        verify(userRepository, times(1)).findByUsername(username);
    }

    @Test
    void testGetUserByUsername_NotFound() {
        // Arrange
        String username = "unknown";
        when(userRepository.findByUsername(username)).thenReturn(Optional.empty());

        // Act & Assert
        assertThrows(UsernameNotFoundException.class, () -> {
            userService.getUserByUsername(username);
        });
    }
}
```

PART 11: MOCKITO KEY METHODS
----------------------------
| Method | Kaam |
|:-------|:-----|
| `when(mock.method()).thenReturn(value)` | Fake response set karna |
| `when(mock.method()).thenThrow(exception)` | Fake exception throw karna |
| `verify(mock, times(n)).method()` | Check karna method `n` baar call hua |
| `verify(mock, never()).method()` | Check karna method kabhi call nahi hua |
| `ArgumentCaptor.forClass()` | Method ko kis argument se call kiya, capture karna |

PART 12: CONTROLLER LAYER TESTING (@WebMvcTest)
-----------------------------------------------
Definition: `@WebMvcTest` sirf **Web Layer** (Controllers) ko test karta hai.
Service aur Repository layers ko **Mock** karna padta hai. Ye lightweight hota hai.

```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.boot.test.autoconfigure.web.servlet.WebMvcTest;
import org.springframework.boot.test.mock.mockito.MockBean;
import org.springframework.test.web.servlet.MockMvc;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.when;
import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.request.MockMvcRequestBuilders.get;
import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.result.MockMvcResultMatchers.*;

@WebMvcTest(ProductController.class)
class ProductControllerTest {

    @Autowired
    private MockMvc mockMvc;  // Fake HTTP requests bhejne ke liye

    @MockBean  // Service ko mock karo (Controller depends on Service)
    private ProductService productService;

    @Test
    void testGetProductById_Success() throws Exception {
        // Arrange
        Long productId = 1L;
        Product mockProduct = new Product(productId, "Laptop", 50000);
        when(productService.getProductById(productId)).thenReturn(mockProduct);

        // Act & Assert
        mockMvc.perform(get("/api/products/{id}", productId))
               .andExpect(status().isOk())
               .andExpect(jsonPath("$.name").value("Laptop"))
               .andExpect(jsonPath("$.price").value(50000));
    }

    @Test
    void testGetProductById_NotFound() throws Exception {
        // Arrange
        Long productId = 99L;
        when(productService.getProductById(productId)).thenThrow(new ProductNotFoundException());

        // Act & Assert
        mockMvc.perform(get("/api/products/{id}", productId))
               .andExpect(status().isNotFound());
    }
}
```

PART 13: REPOSITORY LAYER TESTING (@DataJpaTest)
------------------------------------------------
Definition: `@DataJpaTest` sirf **JPA Components** (Repository) ko test karta hai.
Ye **In-Memory Database** (H2) use karta hai, Real DB nahi.

```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.boot.test.autoconfigure.orm.jpa.DataJpaTest;
import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;
import java.util.Optional;

@DataJpaTest
class UserRepositoryTest {

    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    @Test
    void testFindByUsername_Success() {
        // Arrange
        User user = new User(null, "rahul", "password");
        userRepository.save(user);

        // Act
        Optional<User> found = userRepository.findByUsername("rahul");

        // Assert
        assertThat(found).isPresent();
        assertThat(found.get().getUsername()).isEqualTo("rahul");
    }
}
```

PART 14: TEST COVERAGE KYA HAI?
-------------------------------
Definition: Code Coverage batata hai ki tumhare **kitne percentage code** ko
tests ne execute kiya. Jaise 80% coverage matlab 80% lines of code tests run hui.

Types of Coverage:
- **Line Coverage:** Kitni lines execute hui.
- **Branch Coverage:** Kitne `if-else` branches cover hue.

IntelliJ Mein Coverage Run Karna:
- Right Click on Test Class → **Run 'ClassName' with Coverage**.

PART 15: BEST PRACTICES
-----------------------
1. **F.I.R.S.T Principle:**
   - **F**ast: Tests jaldi run hone chahiye.
   - **I**ndependent: Tests ek doosre pe depend na karein.
   - **R**epeatable: Kitni bhi baar run karo, same result.
   - **S**elf-Validating: Automatic pass/fail, manual check nahi.
   - **T**imely: Code likhte waqt hi test likho (TDD).

2. **One Assert Per Test:** Ek test mein ek hi cheez verify karo.
3. **Meaningful Names:** `testAddition` nahi, `shouldReturnSumWhenTwoPositiveNumbersAdded` likho.
4. **Don't Test External Libraries:** Spring Boot, Hibernate already tested hain.
5. **Avoid Logic in Tests:** `if-else` test mein mat dalo.

